Matthew McConaughey visited the White House to advocate for gun responsibility measures and call on leaders to take action to prevent gun violence. He shared stories from his hometown of Uvalde, Texas, where a mass shooting occurred, and emphasized the importance of keeping children safe. McConaughey discussed the need for mental healthcare, safer schools, and responsible gun ownership. He also expressed support for background checks, raising the minimum age to purchase an AR-15 rifle to 21, waiting periods, and red-flag laws. The President has been briefed on the progress of gun reform negotiations in the Senate and supports the efforts to find a compromise. The article also mentions that the President will sign into law nine bipartisan bills to support veterans and that the administration is investing in affordable high-speed internet access and capital projects to improve connectivity.